[zero_shot][qwen2_5_1_5b_instruct][mmlu] sample 86/100 done id=mmlu_test_11731 prediction='The question involves understanding the legal implications of conveyancing a property with a life estate and a remainder interest under different scenarios. Let\'s break it down:\n\n1. **Grantor-Conveyee Relationship**: The grantor (father) conveys his property to his son "for life" and then to the son\'s heirs upon the son\'s death. This creates a life estate and a remainder interest.\n\n2. **Real Estate Agreement**: Two years later, the son enters into an agreement with his friend to sell the property outright. However, before the settlement date, the friend informs the son that he will not fulfill his part of the agreement due to the son\'s inability to convey a fee simple title.\n\n3. **Rule in Shelley\'s Case**: In jurisdictions adhering to the rule in Shelley\'s Case, if the grantor cannot convey a fee simple title, the grantee may succeed in obtaining specific performance against the grantor.\n\n4. **Analysis**:\n   - **Option A**: The son could not convey marketable title because he was unable to convey a fee simple title.\n   - **Option B**: The son succeeded because he had a fee simple to convey.\n   - **Option C**: The son did not succeed because his heirs need to join in the transaction' gold='B' correct=False
