[zero_shot][qwen2_5_1_5b_instruct][mmlu] sample 93/100 done id=mmlu_test_12665 prediction='Step 1: Understand the difference between parametric and nonparametric statistical tests.\n\nParametric tests assume that the data follows a specific distribution (e.g., normal distribution) and make assumptions about the population parameters such as mean and standard deviation. Nonparametric tests do not rely on these assumptions and instead focus on rank-based statistics or other measures that do not require the assumption of a particular distribution.\n\nStep 2: Analyze each choice to determine which one cannot be correct given the properties of both types of tests.\n\nA. They are used for ordinal and nominal data - This is true because parametric tests typically require interval or ratio data, while nonparametric tests can handle ordinal and nominal data without assuming a specific distribution.\n\nB. They are based on normal distribution - This is false because parametric tests are based on the assumption of normality, whereas nonparametric tests do not make this assumption.\n\nC. They are based on homogeneity of variance - This is true because parametric tests often assume equal variances across groups, but nonparametric tests generally do not have this requirement.\n\nD. They are based on Independence of Observations - This is true because parametric tests also assume independence among observations within groups, while nonparametric tests may relax this assumption.' gold='A' correct=False
