[zero_shot][qwen2_5_1_5b_instruct][mmlu] sample 97/100 done id=mmlu_test_13588 prediction='The tripartite system was introduced in Ireland during the early 20th century as part of educational reforms aimed at improving access to education for all children. It replaced the old single-track system with three separate tracks based on ability.\n\nStep 1: Identify the key elements of the tripartite system.\n- Three distinct types of schools were established: grammar (for academically gifted students), technical (for vocational training), and secondary modern (for general education).\n\nStep 2: Determine which type of school would have selected pupils through an examination.\n- The question asks about selecting pupils for these schools using an "exam."\n\nStep 3: Match the description of the tripartite system with the given choices.\n- Choice A describes popular schools that lie outside one\'s catchment area, which does not align with the structure of the tripartite system.\n- Choice B mentions private, public, and comprehensive schools, but it doesn\'t specify the nature of the exams or the track-based selection process.\n- Choice C accurately describes the three types of schools under the tripartite system: grammar, technical, and secondary modern.\n- Choice D refers to polytechnics, colleges, and universities, which are post-secondary institutions rather than primary schools.\n\nConclusion: The correct choice' gold='C' correct=False
